### The Throw Statement

The `throw` statement lets you **create your own errors**.

---

### Throwing Errors

```js
throw "An error occurred";       // Throws a string
throw 404;                        // Throws a number
throw new Error("Something broke!"); // Throws an Error object
```

> **Best Practice:** Always throw `Error` objects, not strings or numbers. They provide better debugging information.

---

### Custom Error Validation

```js
function divide(a, b) {
  if (b === 0) {
    throw new Error("Cannot divide by zero!");
  }
  if (typeof a !== "number" || typeof b !== "number") {
    throw new TypeError("Both arguments must be numbers");
  }
  return a / b;
}
```

---

### Catching Custom Errors

```js
try {
  let result = divide(10, 0);
  console.log(result);
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof TypeError) {
    console.log("Type error:", error.message);
  } else {
    console.log("General error:", error.message);
  }
}
```

---

### Custom Error Classes

```js
class ValidationError extends Error {
  constructor(message) {
    super(message);
    this.name = "ValidationError";
  }
}

throw new ValidationError("Invalid input!");
```

---

> **Use Case:** Throw errors to enforce rules in your code -- validate inputs, check permissions, verify data integrity.

codeExample:
function checkAge(age) {
  if (age < 0) {
    throw new Error("Age cannot be negative");
  }
  if (age < 18) {
    throw new Error("Must be 18 or older");
  }
  return "Access granted";
}

try {
  console.log(checkAge(-5));
} catch (err) {
  console.log(err.message);
}
